The paper deals with network bargaining games, which are a subfield of game theory. The use of algorithms and computational complexity analysis suggests that the paper belongs to the cs.GT (Computer Science and Game Theory) sub-category. The paper also involves graph theory and optimization, which are relevant to the cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) sub-category. The use of AI techniques and the study of stable solutions suggest that the paper could also belong to the cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) and cs.SI (Social and Information Networks) sub-categories. Finally, the paper involves the study of balanced solutions, which is a topic in the cs.LG (Machine Learning) sub-category.
